{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"body":"[PASS 1 review — G6 Approach soundness, anti-patterns & alternative-selection]\n\nAFFIRMATIONS (G6 criteria this plan satisfies):\n- Mechanism correctness (core path): the resolve→pin-immutable-SHA→faithful-materialize (read-tree into a temp GIT_INDEX_FILE + checkout-index, NOT git archive)→content-addressed cache→run gate→bind SHA flow is logically complete and concurrency-aware. Single-flight, POSIX delete-on-last-close reader safety, atomic dir-rename population, and the flock GC interlock handle the concurrent/eviction/crash edge cases without a check-then-act race. The attested pin write names a real anti-TOCTOU serialization (compare-and-set on the ticket's existing event-append/optimistic-concurrency boundary), not just an assertion.\n- Manifest-channel SHA binding is mechanism-correct and verified against source: `signing._canonical_payload` signs `{v, algorithm, ticket_id, manifest}` and `compute_signature` signs the full `manifest: list[str]` (signing.py:188-206), so a `verified-at-sha:<sha>` MANIFEST STEP enters the signed bytes WITHOUT a `_canonical_payload`/`PAYLOAD_VERSION` change — the \"no prior-signature invalidation\" claim holds. This is a genuinely good design choice (additive, reproducible) over the rejected new-signed-payload-field approach.\n- Fitness-for-purpose: the wrong-branch false-negative that motivated the epic is directly targeted by the AC4 behavioral regression in S3 (attested verdict IDENTICAL regardless of the server's checked-out branch) — a behavioral contract, not a change-detector. local mode preserves the single-dev verify-before-push back-out.\n- Approach selection (alternatives generated and judged): (1) `git archive` materialization — the plan explicitly rejects it on faithfulness (export-ignore/LFS/submodule/export-subst), correct. (2) `git worktree add` per ref instead of a content-addressed snapshot dir — would take worktree/index.lock locks and reintroduce exactly the contention the lock-free no-worktree approach avoids; the chosen approach is defensibly superior on concurrency + blast-radius. Both alternatives discarded; the chosen approach is defensible.\n- Positive rationale is present and strong (immutable SHA = perfect cache key / no staleness; manifest channel chosen to avoid signature invalidation; de-risking order; design grounded against Gitaly/Sourcegraph/Bazel/Nix/in-toto). G6 rationale criterion PASSES — no finding there.\n\nFINDING (mechanism / fitness-for-purpose — the named re-rooting approach under-specifies the plan-review attestation hashing path, so AC1/AC2 \"never the mutable checkout\" may not actually hold for the claim gate):\n\n- [ ] State HOW the pinned-SHA snapshot basis reaches plan-review's `dependency_hashes()` / `_rehash()` / the ADR-0002 claim-gate freshness re-check, since the plan's chosen mechanism (\"re-root the gate's file tools / pai_tools root / cfg.repo_path\") does not cover those three sign/verify-side hashing sites — all of which root on the MUTABLE checkout via `_config.repo_root` (attest.py:106-107, :191-196, :325-326). As decomposed, AC2's reproducibility and AC1's \"no code-reading gate reads the server's working tree in attested mode\" are not achieved for the plan-review claim gate: a signed verdict can hash file_impact from the snapshot while the later freshness re-check re-hashes the same paths from whatever branch/dirty tree the server is on — reintroducing the very moving-checkout false-verdict the epic exists to kill (now on the verify side).\n  - criteria: G6 (mechanism correctness — a hidden read-root divergence that defeats the goal; fitness-for-purpose — solves the named problem for the LLM file-tool gates but not the claim-gate hashing path).\n  - location: parent \"What\" (attested bullet: \"run gate\"), Success Criteria (\"every code-reading gate ... never the server's mutable checkout\"), Acceptance Criteria AC1 + AC2; mechanism owned across S3 fa49 (\"point the gate's file tools (pai_tools root / cfg.repo_path) at the snapshot dir\") and S4b dodgy-luff-quasar (claim-gate↔plan-review ref coherence).\n  - evidence:\n    1. `dependency_hashes()` signs the dep map hashed from `base = str(_config.repo_root(repo_root))` (attest.py:106-107) — the mutable checkout, not a snapshot dir.\n    2. `_rehash()` re-hashes \"at CURRENT working-tree content\" from `_config.repo_root` (attest.py:191-196).\n    3. The ADR-0002 freshness re-check hashes from `_config.repo_root` (attest.py:325-326).\n    4. The plan describes the gate-read mechanism only as re-rooting the \"file tools (pai_tools root / cfg.repo_path)\"; attest.py's hashing path is a separate code root not covered by that phrasing, and no part of the parent text names it as in-scope for the snapshot basis. (This is the same seam the standing S4 30b3 G4 dependency-gap notes; raising it here at G6 because, at the parent level, it is an approach/mechanism completeness gap — the chosen \"re-root file tools\" mechanism is not sufficient to satisfy the plan's own AC1/AC2 for the claim gate.)\n  - suggested_fix: In the parent \"What\"/Acceptance, make the snapshot read-root explicit for the plan-review attestation hashing path (not just the LLM file tools): thread the resolved-SHA snapshot dir as the hash `base` into `dependency_hashes()`, `_rehash()`, and the ADR-0002 freshness re-check in place of `_config.repo_root`, and assign that re-rooting unambiguously to one child (extend S3's re-rooting scope to include plan_review/attest.py, or claim it explicitly in S4b) so AC1/AC2 are mechanically achievable for the claim gate.\n\nNo other G6 findings: the core snapshot/cache/signing mechanism is sound, the named problem is solved, the chosen approach is defensible against the two structurally-different alternatives generated, and positive rationale is present."},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1782531318910274001,"uuid":"c5a2de90-f248-4683-8827-6ce2aac7c008"}